answers.body_markdown:
I wouldn&#39;t recommend it, what is the gain over adding `@Autowired` to writing `Logger logger = LoggerFactory.getLogger(getClass());`. 

That being said you can write an `@Bean` method for a prototype scoped bean and use the [`InjectionPoint`][1] to obtain the information about the class etc. and use that to create a `Logger`. 

```java
@Bean
@Scope(&quot;prototype&quot;)
public Logger logger(InjectionPoint ip) {
  return LoggerFactory.getLogger(ip.getMember().getDeclaringClass());
}
```

This will allow a dynamic (sort of) bean to be created for each `Logger` that is `@Autowired`. 

[1]: https://docs.spring.io/spring-framework/docs/current/javadoc-api/org/springframework/beans/factory/InjectionPoint.html

